Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js project.

## What was implemented:

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics following the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart.

## Changes made:

### 1. Installed dependencies:
- Added `@vercel/analytics` package (v1.4.2) as a production dependency

### 2. Modified files:
- **package.json**: Added `@vercel/analytics` to dependencies
- **package-lock.json**: Updated with new package and dependencies (369 packages added)
- **src/app/layout.tsx**: 
  - Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component at the end of the `<body>` tag, after the `<SiteFooter />` component

## Implementation approach:

1. Fetched the latest installation instructions from Vercel's official documentation
2. Identified this as a Next.js 16.2.9 project using the App Router (has layout.tsx in src/app/)
3. Determined npm as the package manager (package-lock.json present)
4. Installed @vercel/analytics using npm
5. Added the Analytics component to the root layout following App Router best practices
6. Verified the build completes successfully with no new errors
7. Pre-existing linting errors in other components (leaderboard-view.tsx and season-card.tsx) are unrelated to this change

## Next steps for the developer:

To enable analytics data collection:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel (`vercel deploy`)
2. Enable Web Analytics in your Vercel dashboard under the Analytics tab
3. After deployment, verify tracking works by checking the browser's Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view`
4. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard after users visit the site

The Analytics component will automatically track page views and is now ready to use once deployed to Vercel.
